Sealed types, a closed family of subtypes.

A normal class or interface is open. Anyone, anywhere, at any time, can extend it. A sealed type, from Java seventeen, lets you say the opposite: these, and only these, are the types allowed to extend me. And the compiler enforces that list.

You declare a sealed interface Shape that permits exactly Circle, Square, and Triangle, and you make each of those a record that implements Shape. From that point on, no other class anywhere in the world is allowed to implement Shape.

Why does that matter? Because now the compiler knows the complete set of subtypes. That is what lets it check a switch over a shape for exhaustiveness, verifying that you have handled every possible case, which is exactly what we do in the next section.
